## Migration: `Thread.Abort` Timeout → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code aborts a thread exceeding a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop (not just be abandoned)

The above "abandons" the task but doesn't force it to stop. For true cooperative cancellation, pass the token into the work:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token:
```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Without token checks inside `work`, the task runs to completion in the background (leaked thread/resources). Always pass and check the token. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers. Always `using`. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't add token checks, the only true "kill" is `Process.Kill` on a child process. Task abandonment is the pragmatic compromise. |

### What Was Removed

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Replacement |
|--------------------|-------------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` / `CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested`, decide to continue |

The fundamental shift: cancellation is now **cooperative** — the running code must voluntarily check for and honor cancellation requests.
